327","1220–1263":"1220–1263","1222–1284":"1222–1284","1220":"1220","1253":"1253","1264":"1264","1263":"1263","1230":"1230","1284":"1284","1250":"1250","1283":"1283","1294":"1294","1280":"1280","1327":"1327","1249":"1249","1257":"1257","1246":"1246","1245":"1245","1222":"1222","1244":"1244","1309":"1309","1308":"1308","after 1246":"after 1246","1317":"1317","Dunham Massey, Cheshire, England":"Dunham Massey, Cheshire, England","Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, England":"Hatch Beauchamp, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Dunster, Somerset, England":"Dunster, Somerset, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Beauchamp","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Antoine, Jacques, Yves, Andre, Armand, Emile, Fernand, Marcel, Marthe, Remi, Alcide, Camille.","English (of Norman origin) and French: habitational name from any of several places in France, for example in Manche and Somme, that are named with Old French <i>beu</i>, <i>bel</i> ‘fair, lovely’ + <i>champ(s)</i> ‘field, plain’ (from Latin <i>bello campo</i> ‘beautiful field’). In English the surname is generally pronounced   Beecham  . Compare   Bushaw  .","English: in some cases, an Anglo-Norman French adaptation of Scottish   Campbell  , by translation into French of the folk etymology <i>de campo bello</i> ‘from the fair field’."],"variants":[{"name":"Beecham","meanings":["English (Lincolnshire): variant of   Beauchamp  , reflecting the normal English pronunciation."]},{"name":"Beachem","meanings":["English (Somerset and Gloucestershire): variant of   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Beachum","meanings":["Altered form of English   Beauchamp  ."]},{"name":"Bagent","meanings":["English:","possibly a colloquial pronunciation of   Beauchamp   or   Beecham  . Old French <i>Beau-</i> often appears as <i>Be(e)-</i> in English surnames. The <i>-ch-</i> has been voiced and excrescent <i>-t</i> has been added.","perhaps an Anglicized form 